SIMON: SImple Measurement ONtology is designed to represent measurements of one, two or n dimensions. E.g., distance: meters, weight: kilograms, time: seconds; speed: miles per hour, wages: dollars per hour; acceleration: meters per second per second. Although there are other vocabularies that exist in this domain they are large and complex. That is of course completely appropriate for certain types of problems but for many problems I've encountered recently with clients a smaller, leaner, easier vocabulary is useful, that is the niche that SIMON attempts to fill.
Two main classes: measurement which records a specific measurement such as distance, speed, or acceleration and units which record units such as meters, miles per hour, and meters per second per second. Each measurement also has a data property with range xsd:dateTime to record when the measurement was taken if desired. The third top level class is PunnedClass. This is for classes that have puns in order to assert values on them. This is used to record the canonical unit for each type of measurement.
The canonical unit is used by some of the SWRL rules. There are SWRL rules defined to translate from various measurements to their canonical value. For example the canonical unit for DistanceMeasurements is currently set to Meter. To change the canonical unit all that is necessary is to clone (or edit) the existing rules and 1) Change the test for the canonical unit in each rule to the desired new canonical unit and 2) Change the computation to the appropriate conversion factor. Canonical units are used to minimize the number of rules required to order different kinds of Measurements.
The ordering on measurements is defined by various transitive object properties such as greaterThan with inverses such as lessThan. The order is imposed on the canonical value via fairly simple SWRL rules (the rules can be simple due to the transitive and inverse characteristics of the property and the fact that all Measurements are transformed into a canonical unit.
See the README file at: https://github.com/mdebellis/SIMON-A-Simple-Measurement-Vocabulary for more information on how to use and modify this vocabulary.

This relation is maintained by SWRL rules that impose an order on the hasCanonicalValue data property. hasCanonicalValue is used rather than hasValue in order to impose the correct order on measurements that use different units.
This is automatically maintained by the reasoner based on the value of its inverse lessThan.. See that property comment for more info.

This relation is maintained by SWRL rules that impose an order on the hasCanonicalValue data property. hasCanonicalValue is used rather than hasValue in order to impose the correct order on measurements that use different units. Note that lessThanOrEqualTo is not set by the SWRL rules because it is automatically maintained because it is the inverse of this property. We do have to test for both directions (greater and less) though because otherwise we risk not ordering a maximum or minimum value. Hence, we test for greaterThanOrEqualTo for the > direction and lessThan for the < direction.
Records the canonical unit for a certain type of measurement. As a result the domain is PunnedClass. For example, the hasCanonicalUnit for the punned class DistanceMeasurement is Meter.

Measurements involving 2 or more units are constructed as follows. To create an n-unit measure one first creates the appropriate n-1 unit measure and then makes that measure the value of hasMeasurement. E.g., to create a DoubleUnitMeasurement one creates a SingleUnitMeasurement and makes that Measurement the value of hasMeasurement for the DoubleUnitMeasurement. Similarly to create a TripleUnitMeasurement one creates the appropriate DoubleUnitMeasurement and makes it the value of hasMeasurement.
Some specific examples: To create "5 miles per hour" create the SingleUnitMeasurement "5 miles" and make it the value of hasMeasurement. To create "5 miles per second per second" creat the DoubleUnitMeasurement "5 miles per second" and make it the value of hasMeasurement.

The first unit for a Measurement. E.g., for "5 miles", "5 miles per hour" and "5 miles per second per second" the first unit is always Mile. Note that this value does not need to be explicitly set. It will be inferred by the reasoner based on the define classes for various Measurements.

The canonical value is calculated by SWRL rules. The SWRL rules check the hasCanonicalUnit for various Measurements and does the appropriate calculation. To change the canonical unit one needs to edit the value of the hasCanonicalUnit property on the punned class for that Measurement and then clone (or edit) the appropriate SWRL rules, changing the test for the canoncial unit and the calculation for the conversion.
Records the measured value before conversion to canonical value. Also, used by SPARQL rules to automatically generate names for the Measurement instances.
The date and time that the Measurement was made. An optional property.

Used for some SPARQL transformations that construct the rdfs:label value for instances of the Measurement class. For these names we often want the name of the unit to be in plural form rather than in the standard singular form so this value is defined and used in that situation. E.g., for the measurement kph5 we want it to have the rdfs:label: "5 Kilometers per Hour" so we construct that name in SPARQL by concatenating the hasMeasuredValue with the pluralName of its first unit followed by the string "per" followed by the singular rdfs:label of its second unit.
Measurements involving 2 dimensions. E.g., kilometers per hour

A Measurement is an implementation of the n-ary relation pattern. A Measurement of one dimension is a 4-ary relation: <MeasuredThing, Value, Unit, Time>. The MeasuredThing is domain dependent and not included in this vocabulary ontology. The value and time are represented as data properties with range xsd:decimal and xsd:dateTime respectively. The Unit is an instance of the Unit class. For one dimensional measurements this is stored in the object property hasUnit1. To add additional dimensions we add additional units (hasUnit2, hasUnit3, etc.).
Note that the axioms on various Measurement classes provide some default value reasoning. E.g., the axiom for MeterMeasurement is: "DistanceMeasurement and (hasUnit1 value Meter)" so when one creates an instance of MeterMeasurement its hasUnit1 data property is automatically set to Meter.

Class for individuals that are puns of classes. Used for the property hasCanonicalUnit which records the canonical unit to transform values to for specific kinds of Measurements. E.g., the canonical unit for the punned class DistanceMeasurement is Meter.

Used for the property hasCanonicalUnit which records the canonical unit to transform values to for specific kinds of Measurements. E.g., the canonical unit for the punned class DistanceMeasurement is Meter.
Measurements involving just one dimension: e.g., time, distance, weight
Measurements involving 3 dimensions. E.g., acceleration kilometers per second per second
The parent class for all types of units such as Mile, Kilometer, Gram, Second, etc.
